    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-04-28T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-04-28T08:00:00-05:00" n="369"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d369">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">396.1 GE/4–2854: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret<lb/>priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-04-28T14:00:00+01:00"
                            >April 28, 1954—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Dulte1">Dulte</gloss> 17. For General <persName
                        corresp="#p_SWB1">Smith</persName> from Secretary.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>(1)</label>
                    <item>Re your <gloss target="#t_Tedul1">Tedul</gloss> 14,<note n="1"
                            xml:id="d369fn1">Dated Apr. 27, <ref target="#pg_588">p.
                            588</ref>.</note> we are now working on draft cable giving our overall
                        views on entire subject of intervention and hope to have it dispatched from
                        here by seven o’clock tonight.<note n="2" xml:id="d369fn2">Telegram <gloss
                                target="#t_Dulte1">Dulte</gloss> 21, Apr. 29, <ref target="#pg_605"
                                >p. 605</ref>.</note> We will at that time include our specific
                        comments on your recommendation contained <gloss target="#t_Tedul1"
                            >Tedul</gloss> 2.<note n="3" xml:id="d369fn3">In telegram <gloss
                                target="#t_Tedul1">Tedul</gloss> 2 (Apr. 24, in <ref
                                target="frus1952-54v13p1">volume <hi rend="smallcaps">xiii</hi>
                            </ref>), the Acting Secretary recommended that military representatives
                            of the United States, the United Kingdom, France, Australia, and New
                            Zealand appraise the military situation and examine possible courses of
                            military action “aimed to hold remainder Southeast Asia.” (790.5/4–2454)
                            In telegram <gloss target="#t_Dulte1">Dulte</gloss> 25, Apr. 29, not
                            printed, Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName>
                            informed Acting Secretary <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">Smith</persName>
                            that he did “not believe at this moment in present situation we should
                            propose constitution high level military commission of US, <gloss
                                target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss>, France, Australia, New Zealand and
                            Thailand.” (Conference files, lot 60 D 627, <gloss target="#t_CF1"
                                >CF</gloss> 264) For documentation on the five–power military
                            consultations, see <ref target="frus1952-54v12p1#pg_1">vol. <hi
                                    rend="smallcaps">xii</hi>, pp. 1</ref> ff.</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>(2)</label>
                    <item>Would appreciate having promptly a summary of what transpired at
                        President’s meeting with Congressional leaders last Monday on the subject of
                            Indochina.<note n="4" xml:id="d369fn4">Received that day in telegram
                                <gloss target="#t_Tedul1">Tedul</gloss> 16, Apr. 28. <ref
                                target="#pg_599">p. 599</ref>.</note> Would also like reaction of
                        President and Security Council on my views as expressed Geneva <gloss
                            target="#t_Dulte1">Dulte</gloss> 3.<note n="5" xml:id="d369fn5">In
                            telegram <gloss target="#t_Dulte1">Dulte</gloss> 3 (Apr. 25, in <ref
                                target="frus1952-54v13p1">volume <hi rend="smallcaps">xiii</hi>
                            </ref>), Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName>
                            outlined his reasons for believing that “it is my opinion that armed
                            intervention by executive action is not warranted.” (751G.5/4–2554) A
                            handwritten notation on the source text indicated that telegram <gloss
                                target="#t_Dulte1">Dulte</gloss> 3 was answered in telegram <gloss
                                target="#t_Tedul1">Tedul</gloss> 15 (Apr. 28. <ref target="#d368">
                                <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>
                            </ref>) and in telegram <gloss target="#t_Tedul1">Tedul</gloss> 16 (Apr.
                            28, <ref target="#pg_599">p. 599</ref>).</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>(3)</label>
                    <item>Re your <gloss target="#t_Tedul1">Tedul</gloss> 10,<note n="6"
                            xml:id="d369fn6">Not printed. Telegram <gloss target="#t_Tedul1"
                                >Tedul</gloss> 10 contained information of a personal nature between
                            Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName> and Under
                            Secretary <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">Smith</persName> pertaining to an
                            appointment to the Department of State. (Conference files, lot 60 D 627,
                                <gloss target="#t_CF1">CF</gloss> 241)</note> I have no objection
                        and delighted you have made such progress. I will look forward to talking
                        with him on my return.</item>
                    <label>(4)</label>
                    <item>I will try and reach decision on best date for your arrival at Geneva by
                        tomorrow. It is difficult at this point to make any judgment on how long I
                        should stay.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
